{"id":"2211.02865","submitter":"Ameneh Farhadian","authors":"Ameneh Farhadian and Hamid Reza Fanai","title":"A Simple Explanation for the Goldbach Conjecture","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.NT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this paper, a simple explanation for the Goldbach Conjecture is given. We\nhave shown that the probability of violating the conjecture not only for the\nprime numbers, but also for any subset of natural numbers whose distribution is\nsimilar to the prime numbers is negligible. This result makes it possible to\ngeneralize the conjecture to any subset of natural numbers whose distribution\nis similar to the prime numbers. Additionally, we selected several new subsets\nwhose distribution amongst the natural numbers are similar to the prime numbers\nby randomly addition of +1 and -1 to the prime numbers and checked the Goldbach\nconjecture for every even integer less than $2 \\times 10^8$ by computer. As it\nwas expected, the Goldbach conjecture holds true for these new reconstructed\nsets, as well. Consequently, the conjecture can be generalized to any subset of\nnatural numbers whose distribution is similar to the prime numbers. That is\n\"being prime\" is not necessary for the conjecture to hold for the instances.\nThis fact brings to mind the idea that perhaps what makes the Conjecture to\nhold for the instances is \"probability\", not number theory facts.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 5 Nov 2022 09:58:49 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 4 Feb 2023 08:38:32 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-02-07"}
{"id":"2211.02866","submitter":"Gunther Cornelissen","authors":"Jakub Byszewski and Gunther Cornelissen","title":"Multiband linear cellular automata and endomorphisms of algebraic vector\n  groups","comments":"11 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.DS cs.FL math.AG math.NT nlin.CG","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  We propose a correspondence between certain multiband linear cellular\nautomata - models of computation widely used in the description of physical\nphenomena - and endomorphisms of certain algebraic unipotent groups over finite\nfields. The correspondence is based on the construction of a universal element\nspecialising to a normal generator for any finite field. We use this\ncorrespondence to deduce new results concerning the temporal dynamics of such\nautomata, using our prior, purely algebraic, study of the endomorphism ring of\nvector groups. These produce 'for free' a formula for the number of fixed\npoints of the $n$-iterate in terms of the $p$-adic valuation of $n$, a\ndichotomy for the Artin-Mazur dynamical zeta function, and an asymptotic\nformula for the number of periodic orbits. Since multiband linear cellular\nautomata simulate higher order linear automata (in which states depend on\nfinitely many prior temporal states, not just the direct predecessor), the\nresults apply equally well to that class.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 5 Nov 2022 10:05:58 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-11-08"}
